  "title": "La Rochefoucauld §laroch_382: Our actions are like the rhymed ends of blank verses (Bouts-Rimes) where to e...",
  "body": "Our actions are like the rhymed ends of blank verses (Bouts-Rimes) where to each one puts what construction he pleases. [The Bouts-Rimes was a literary game popular in the 17th and 18th centuries--the rhymed words at the end of a line being given for others to fill up. Thus Horace Walpole being given, \"brook, why, crook, I,\" returned the burlesque verse-- \"I sits with my toes in a Brook, And if any one axes me Why? I gies 'em a rap with my Crook, 'Tis constancy makes me, ses I.\"]",
